<h3 class=3D"h3" id=3D"sec24"><a id=3D"h35"></a>SUMMARY</h3>
<p class=3D"noindent">This chapter has discussed the roles and responsibili=
ties of a typical BA, whilst highlighting the fact that the specific duties=
 will often depend on the demands and the context of a specific organisatio=
n. The chapter outlined common areas of BA involvement, including stakehold=
er management, elicitation, strategic analysis, requirements analysis, docu=
mentation and <a id=3D"page_94"></a>management, solution evaluation, benefi=
ts realisation and leadership.</p>
<p class=3D"noindent">The chapter also highlighted the importance of stayin=
g current, as the BA role is continually evolving. This includes keeping up=
 with developments within your industry sector, general technological trend=
s and new developments within the business analysis profession. It should b=
e noted that there are other disciplines that work closely with BAs, and th=
ere are often opportunities for collaboration. As T-shaped practitioners, w=
e may even gain some knowledge and experience from these areas and use them=
 in our BA work.</p>
<p class=3D"noindent">The chapter concluded by reflecting on the fact that =
there are many flavours of business analysis, both inside and outside proje=
cts. <a href=3D"https://learning.oreilly.com/library/view/business-analyst-=
/9781780174280/13_chapter03.xhtml#tab3-1">Table 3.1</a> provides a guide to=
 whether or not the role is for you.</p>
<p class=3D"noindent">Having discussed the typical roles and responsibiliti=
es of a BA, we can now move on to discuss the typical business analysis fra=
meworks, tools and techniques that are used.</p>
